======================================================================
THE 3^k LOWER BOUND THEOREM
======================================================================

THEOREM: If tournament T has k mutually vertex-disjoint odd
directed cycles, then H(T) >= 3^k.

PROOF: k disjoint cycles => alpha_j >= C(k,j) for 0<=j<=k
  H = I(Omega,2) >= sum C(k,j)*2^j = (1+2)^k = 3^k.

COROLLARY: The minimum H for maximum disjoint cycle count k:
  k=0: H >= 3^0 = 1
  k=1: H >= 3^1 = 3
  k=2: H >= 3^2 = 9
  k=3: H >= 3^3 = 27
  k=4: H >= 3^4 = 81
  k=5: H >= 3^5 = 243
  k=6: H >= 3^6 = 729
  k=7: H >= 3^7 = 2187

APPLICATION TO PERMANENT GAPS:
  H=7:  T=(7-1)/2=3.  Since 3 < (3^2-1)/2=4, alpha_2=0.
        Only decomposition (3,0). Blocked by splicing lemma.
  H=21: T=(21-1)/2=10. Since 10 < (3^3-1)/2=13, alpha_3=0.
        Only quadratic decompositions. All 4 blocked.
  H=63: T=31 > 13. alpha_3>=1 possible. (21,3,1) works at n=9.
        NOT a permanent gap (found at n=8).

======================================================================
VERIFICATION: H >= 3^k at small n
======================================================================

n=3 (EXHAUSTIVE): violations = 0
  k=1: H=3^1=3 achieved 2 times (min ratio = 1.0000)

n=4 (EXHAUSTIVE): violations = 0
  k=1: H=3^1=3 achieved 16 times (min ratio = 1.0000)

n=5 (EXHAUSTIVE): violations = 0
  k=1: H=3^1=3 achieved 120 times (min ratio = 1.0000)

n=6 (SAMPLED (5000)): violations = 0
  k=1: H=3^1=3 achieved 153 times (min ratio = 1.0000)
  k=2: H=3^2=9 achieved 5 times (min ratio = 1.0000)

n=7 (SAMPLED (5000)): violations = 0
  k=1: H=3^1=3 achieved 19 times (min ratio = 1.0000)
  k=2: H=3^2=9 achieved 6 times (min ratio = 1.0000)

n=8 (SAMPLED (5000)): violations = 0
  k=1: H=3^1=3 achieved 1 times (min ratio = 1.0000)
  k=2: H=3^2=9 achieved 1 times (min ratio = 1.0000)

n=9 (SAMPLED (5000)): violations = 0
  k=1: min H/3^1 = 7.6667 (min H = 23)
  k=2: min H/3^2 = 3.0000 (min H = 27)
  k=3: min H/3^3 = 3.4444 (min H = 93)

======================================================================
CONNECTION TO 2-3 NUMBER THEORY
======================================================================

The 3^k bound comes from (1+x)^k at x=2.
If we evaluated at x=1 instead: I(G,1) >= (1+1)^k = 2^k.
At x=3: I(G,3) >= 4^k.

The tournament evaluation x=2 gives EXACTLY the base-3 hierarchy!
  x=2: bound is 3^k = (2+1)^k
  This is WHY 3 is the key: 3 = evaluation_point + 1 = 2+1

The hierarchy of achievable H values:
  Level 0: H in {1} (alpha(Omega) = 0, no cycles)
  Level 1: H in [3, 8] odd (alpha(Omega) >= 1, at most 1 cycle island)
    Gap: H=7 (blocked at quadratic level)
  Level 2: H in [9, 26] odd (alpha(Omega) >= 2, can have disjoint pair)
    Gap: H=21 (blocked at cubic level)
  Level 3: H in [27, 80] odd (alpha(Omega) >= 3)
    No gaps! cubic I.P. provides enough flexibility
  Level 4+: no gaps.

The gap at level 1 is H = 2^2 + 2 + 1 = 7 = Phi_3(2)
The gap at level 2 is H = 3 * 7 = 21 = 3 * Phi_3(2)

Why 3*7 = 21 specifically?
  T = 10 is the largest value below (3^3-1)/2 = 13 that
  has NO valid quadratic decomposition.
  T=11 works via (11,0) or (9,1)
  T=12 works via (12,0)
  T=10: (10,0) blocked, (8,1) blocked, (6,2) blocked, (4,3) blocked

Connection to cyclotomic polynomials:
  Phi_1(2) = 1
  Phi_2(2) = 3
  Phi_3(2) = 7
  Phi_4(2) = 5
  Phi_6(2) = 3
  H=7 = Phi_3(2)
  H=21 = Phi_2(2) * Phi_3(2) = 3 * 7
  H=7 is the value of x^2+x+1 at x=2
  H=21 is the value of (x+1)(x^2+x+1) = x^3+2x^2+2x+1 at x=2 = 8+8+4+1
  Note: x^3+2x^2+2x+1 = (x^3-1)/(x-1) + x^2 + x
  Actually: 21 = 2^4 + 2^2 + 2^0 = 16+4+1 (binary: 10101)

======================================================================
WHY T=10 IS THE UNIQUE LEVEL-2 GAP
======================================================================

At level 2 (9 <= H < 27, i.e., 4 <= T <= 12):
  T=4: achievable as (4,0) at n=5 or (2,1) at n=6
  T=5: achievable as (5,0) at n=5
  T=6: achievable as (6,0)
  T=7: achievable as (7,0)
  T=8: achievable as (8,0) or (6,1)
  T=9: achievable as (9,0)
  T=10: BLOCKED -- all 4 decompositions impossible
  T=11: achievable as (11,0) or (9,1)
  T=12: achievable as (12,0)

The pattern: (a1, 0) is achievable for all a1 != 3, 10.
And (a1, a2) with a2 > 0 starts at T=4.
So T=10 is blocked because:
  1. (10, 0) requires alpha_1=10, alpha_2=0 -- but alpha_1=10 forces alpha_2>=2
  2. (8, 1) never occurs as an achievable (alpha_1, alpha_2) pair
  3. (6, 2) never occurs as an achievable pair
  4. (4, 3) never occurs as an achievable pair

The achievable alpha_1 values with alpha_2=0:
  n=5: {0,1,2,4,5,6,7} -- note 3 MISSING!
  n=6: {0,1,2,4,5,6,7,8,9,11,12,16} -- note 3,10 MISSING!
  n=7: {0,1,2,4,5,6,7,8,9,11,12,13,15,16,18,19,22,23,24,25,34,...}
        -- note 3 has min_a2=2, 10 has min_a2=2

CONJECTURE: alpha_1=3 and alpha_1=10 are the ONLY values
that PERMANENTLY force alpha_2 >= 2 at all n.
